rica]]'' #18-21, 53, 54, ''Annual'' #1 (penciller); #23-25, 27-28 (writer/penciller) (2008-2011)  \n* ''[[Mystery in Space]]'' #117 (inker) (1981)    \n* ''[[Outsiders (comics)|Outsiders]]'' #10 (artist); #13 (inker) (1986)  \n* ''[[Planetary (comics)|Planetary/JLA: Terra Occulta]]'' #1 (artist) (2002) \n* ''Power of Shazam'' HC  (writer/artist) (1994)  \n* ''[[Captain Marvel (DC Comics)|Power of Shazam]]'' #1-41, ''Annual'' #1 (writer); #42-47, #1,000,000 (writer/penciller) (1995-1999)  \n* ''[[Red Menace (comics)|Red Menace]]'' #1-6 (penciller) (2007)  \n* ''[[Secret Origins]]'' #1 (inker) (1986)  \n* ''[[Sergio Aragon\u00e9s]] Destroys DC'' #1 (inker) (1996)  \n* ''[[Showcase (comics)|Showcase '95]]'' #10 (writer) (1995)  \n* ''Showcase '96'' #7 (writer) (1996) \n* ''[[Superman vol. 2|Superman]]'' vol. 2 #31, 34-35, 39, 110 (writer); #36-38, 40-47, 49-55 (writer/penciller); #57 (inker); #226 (artist) (1989-2006)  \n* ''[[Superman/Batman]]'' #72-75 (artist) (2010)  \n* ''Superman: [[Secret Files and Origins]]'' #1 (inker) (1998)  \n* ''Superman: The Earth Stealers'' #1 (inker) (1988)  \n* ''Superman: The Legacy of Superman'' #1  (writer) (1993)  \n* ''[[Superman: The Man of Steel]]'' #1 (inker); #1,000,000 (writer) (1991-1998)  \n* ''[[Superman: The Wedding Album]]'' #1 (inker) (1996)  \n* ''[[T.H.U.N.D.E.R. Agents]]'' #2 (artist) (2012)  \n* ''Tales of the Sinestro Corps: Superman Prime'' #1 (artist) (2007)  \n* ''[[Trinity (comic book)|Trinity]]'' #3-4, 16 (inker) (2008)  \n* ''[[Weird War Tales]]'' #99-100, 102-103, 106 (inker) (1981)  \n* ''[[Weird Worlds (comics)|Weird Worlds]]'' vol. 2 #1 (artist) (2011)  \n* ''[[Wonder Woman]]'' #294 ([[Huntress (Helena Wayne)|Huntress]] backup stories) (inker) (1982)\n* ''Wonder Woman'' vol. 2 #189-194 (penciller) (2003)  \n* ''[[Worlds' Finest]]'' #5  (artist) (2012)  \n* ''[[Zero Hour: Crisis in Time]]'' #4-0  (inker) (1994)\n\n====America's Best Comics====\n* ''[[Tom Strong]]'' #5, 20-21 (penciller); #22, 31-32 (artist) (1999-2005)  \n* ''Tom Strong's Terrific Tales'' #3, 6  (artist) (2002-2003)  \n* ''[[Top 10 (comics)|Top 10]]: Beyond the Farthest Precinct'' #1-5 (artist) (2005-2006)\n{{div col end}}\n\n===First Comics===\n* ''[[Grimjack]]'' #10 (artist) (1985)\n\n===Image Comics===\n* ''Action Planet Comics'' #3 (writer/artist) (1997) \n* ''The Messenger'' (one-shot) (writer/artist) (2000)\n* ''Phantom Force'' #2 (inker) (1994)  \n* ''[[WildStar (Image Comics)|WildStar]]: Sky Zero'' #1-4 (penciller) (1993)\n* ''[[WildStar (Image Comics)|WildStar]]'' #1 ([[variant cover]] art inker) (1995)\n\n===Marvel Comics===\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* ''[[The Avengers (comic book)|The Avengers]]'' vol. 3 #16-18 (writer/penciller) (1999)  \n* ''[[Captain America]]'' vol. 3 #32 (artist) (Aug. 2000)\n* ''Captain America and the Invaders: Bahamas Triangle'' (artist) (2019)  \n* ''Domination Factor: Avengers'' #2, 4, 6, 8 (writer/penciller) (1999-2000)  \n* ''[[Fantastic Four]]'' #276-283 (inker); #294-296 (penciler) (1985-1986)  \n* ''[[The Incredible Hulk (comic book)|Hulk]]'' #9-11 (writer) (1999-2000)  \n* ''[[Maximum Security (comics)|Maximum Security]]'' #1-3 (penciler) (2000-2001)  \n* ''Maximum Security: Dangerous Planet'' #1  (penciler) (2000) \n* ''[[Thor (Marvel Comics)|Thor]]'' vol. 2 #9 (inker) (1999)\n* ''Thor 2000'' #1 (artist) (2000)\n* ''[[U.S. Agent (comics)|U.S. Agent]]'' #1-3 (writer/penciller) (2001) \n* ''[[What The--?!]]'' #2 (inker) (1988)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*[http://www.jerryordway.com/ Jerry Ordway blog]\n*[http://www.mikesamazingworld.com/mikes/features/creator.php?creatorid=67 Jerry Ordway] at Mike's Amazing World of DC Comics\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070929141052/http://marvel.com/catalog/?artist=Jerry%20Ordway Jerry Ordway on Marvel.com]\n*[http://www.maelmill-insi.de/UHBMCC/namo7.htm#N556 Jerry Ordway] at the Unofficial Handbook of Marvel Comics Creators\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20180510120132/http://www.fantasticfourheadquarters.co.uk/blog/jerry-ordway-interview Interview at Fantastic Four Headquarters]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box | title=''[[All-Star Squadron]]'' artist| before= [[Adrian Gonzales]]| after=[[Rick Hoberg]]| years=1983\u20131984}}\n{{succession box|title=''[[Infinity, Inc.]]'' artist|before= n/a| after=[[Don Newton]]| years=1984\u20131985}}\n{{succession box|title=''[[Fantastic Four]]'' inker|before= [[Al Gordon]]| after= Al Gordon| years=1985}}\n{{succession box|title=''[[Superman (comic book)|The Adventures of Superman]]'' artist|before=n/a| after=[[Dan Jurgens]]| years=1987\u20131989}}\n{{succession box|title=''The Adventures of Superman'' writer|before=[[John Byrne (comics)|John Byrne]]| after=Dan Jurgens| years=1988\u20131989}}\n{{succession box|title=''[[Superman vol. 2|Superman]]'' vol. 2 writer/artist|before= [[Roger Stern]] (as writer)<br>[[Kerry Gammill]] (as artist)|after=Dan Jurgens| years=1989\u20131991}}\n{{succession box|title=''The Adventures of Superman'' writer|before= Dan Jurgens|after=[[Karl Kesel]]| years=1991\u20131993}}\n{{succession box|title=''[[The Incredible Hulk (comic book)|Hulk]]'' writer|before=John Byrne|after=[[Paul Jenkins (writer)|Paul Jenkins]]|years=1999\u20132000<br/>(with [[Ron Garney]])}}\n{{succession box|title=''[[Wonder Woman]]'' artist|before=[[Phil Jimenez]]|after= [[Drew Johnson (comics)|Drew Johnson]]|years= 2003}}\n{{end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ordway, Jerry}}\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:American comics artists]]\n[[Category:American comics writers]]\n[[Category:Artists from Milwaukee]]\n[[Category:Comics inkers]]\n[[Category:Inkpot Award winners]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toWildcat (disambiguation)(link changed toWildcat (DC Comics)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jerry_Ordway"}
{"title_page": "Yellow wattlebird", "text_new": "{{speciesbox\n| name = Yellow wattlebird\n| image = Anthochaera paradoxa.jpg\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=IUCN>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22704469/0 |title=''Anthochaera paradoxa'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| genus = Anthochaera\n| species = paradoxa\n| authority = ([[Francois-Marie Daudin|Daudin]], 1800)\n| synonyms = ''Corvus paradoxus'' <small>Daudin, 1800</small>\n}}\n\nThe '''yellow wattlebird''' (''Anthochaera paradoxa'') is a species of [[bird]] in the honeyeater family, [[Meliphagidae]].<ref name=IUCN/> Other names include the long or Tasmanian wattlebird.<ref name=\"Pizzey\">{{cite book |author=Graham Pizzey |author-link=Graham Pizzey |year=1980 |title=[[A Field Guide to the Birds of Australia (Pizzey)|A Field Guide to the Birds of Australia]] |location=Australia |publisher=[[Angus and Robertson]] |isbn=9780691084831}}</ref>\n\n==Taxonomy==\nFrench zoologist, [[Fran\u00e7ois Marie Daudin]], described the yellow wattlebird in 1800 as ''Corvus paradoxus''.\n\n==Description==\nThe yellow wattlebird is the largest of the honeyeaters,<ref name=\"Simpson\">{{cite journal |author1=Ken Simpson  |author2=Nicolas Day  |lastauthoramp=yes |year=2004 |title=[[Field Guide to the Birds of Australia (Simpson & Day)|Field Guide to the Birds of Australia]] |edition=7th |location=Princeton, NJ |publisher=[[Princeton University Press]] |isbn=9780691120492}}</ref> and is endemic to Tasmania. They are usually {{convert|37.5|-|45|cm|0}} long.<ref name=\"Pizzey\"/> They are named for the [[Wattle (anatomy)|wattles]] hanging from the cheeks.<ref name=MM>Morcombe, Michael (2012) Field guide to Australian birds. Pascal Press, Glebe, NSW. Revised edition. ISBN 978174021417-9</ref> Yellow wattlebirds are slim birds with a short, strong bill.<ref name=\"Backyard\"/> They have a white face and black-streaked crown.<ref name=\"Simpson\"/> They also have a long, pendulous yellow-orange wattle.<ref name=\"Simpson\"/> The wattle becomes brighter during the breeding season.<ref name=\"Backyard\"/> They have dark wings and a yellow belly,<ref name=\"Simpson\"/> whereas the upperparts are grey to dusky brown.<ref name=\"Pizzey\"/> The female yellow wattlebird is much smaller than the male.<ref name=\"Simpson\"/> The young yellow wattlebirds have much smaller wattles, a paler head, and a browner underbelly than the adult birds.<ref name=\"Backyard\"/> Yellow wattlebirds are active and acrobatic with a strong flight.<ref name=\"Pizzey\"/> They are fairly tame birds and often enter gardens looking for food.<ref name=\"Pizzey\"/>\n\nThe yellow wattlebird is similar in appearance to the [[little wattlebird]] and the [[red wattlebird]].\n\n==Voice==\nHarsh, raucous and grating, their calls have often been compared to a person [[coughing]] or [[belching]], <ref name=\"Pizzey\"/> with a gurgling ''growk'' or repeated ''clok'' sound<ref name=MM></ref>\n\n==Breeding==\nYellow wattlebirds nest in breeding pairs and aggressively defend their territories from other birds.<ref name=\"Backyard\"/> The nest of the yellow wattlebird is made by the female alone,<ref name=\"Backyard\"/> and is a large, open saucer-shaped structure made of twigs and bark that are bound by wool.<ref name=\"Pizzey\"/> The inside of the nest is lined with wool and grass.<ref name=\"Pizzey\"/> The nests can be up to {{convert|13|cm}} high and are found in trees or shrubs.<ref name=\"Pizzey\"/> Yellow wattlebirds lay 2\u20133 eggs that are salmon-red, spotted and blotched red-brown, purplish-red and blue-grey.<ref name=\"Pizzey\"/> Both the males and females incubate the egg and feed the young.<ref name=\"Backyard\"/>\n\n==Habitat==\nYellow wattlebirds live in a variety of habitats including both dry and wet forests, and from sea level to the [[subalpine zone]].<ref name=\"Backyard\"/> They live in coastal [[heath]]s, forests and gardens near ''[[Eucalyptus]]'' trees.<ref name=\"Simpson\"/> They also can be found in mountain shrubberies and open woodlands, particularly those dominated by ''[[Banksia]]''.<ref name=\"Pizzey\"/> They have also been known to occur on [[golf course]]s, and in [[orchard]]s, parks and gardens.<ref name=\"Pizzey\"/>\n\n==Range==\nYellow wattlebirds are common in Tasmania, especially in the eastern and central areas.<ref name=\"Backyard\">{{cite web |url=http://birdsinbackyards.net/finder/display.cfm?id=288 |title=Yellow Wattlebird |publisher=Birds in Backyards |date=11 April 2006 |accessdate=28 April 2008}}</ref> They are uncommon on [[King Island (Tasmania)|King Island]], and two possible sightings recorded on the southern [[Mornington Peninsula]] in [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]] lack material evidence.<ref name=\"Pizzey\"/>\n\n==Ecology==\nYellow wattlebirds feed on the [[nectar]] of eucalypts and banksias, fruit, [[insect]]s, [[spider]]s, [[Honeydew (secretion)|honeydew]] and manna (crystallised plant sap).<ref name=\"Action\">{{cite web |url=http://www.environment.gov.au/biodiversity/threatened/publications/action/birds2000/pubs/yellow-wattlebird.pdf |format=[[Portable Document Format|PDF]] |title=The Action Plan for Australian Birds 2000: Recovery Outline \u2013 Yellow Wattlebird (King Island) |publisher=[[Department of the Environment, Water, Heritage and the Arts]] |date=27 April 2008 |accessdate=28 April 2008}}</ref> They forage from all levels of the canopy from the ground to the top of the trees.<ref name=\"Backyard\"/> However, the blossoming of eucalyptus trees can be highly irregular in time and place causing considerable changes from year to year in the breeding distribution of yellow wattlebirds, which rely on the nectar from the eucalyptus trees as a main source of food.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=M. G. Ridpath  |author2=R. E. Moreau  |lastauthoramp=yes |year=1966 |title=The birds of Tasmania: ecology and evolution |journal=[[Ibis (journal)|Ibis]] |volume=108 |issue=3 |pages=348\u2013393 |doi=10.1111/j.1474-919X.1966.tb07349.x}}</ref> Therefore, the most likely threat to the yellow wattlebird is unusual climatic conditions that can reduce food availability suddenly.<ref name=\"Action\"/> Yellow wattlebirds can pollinate eucalyptus trees by carrying pollen in their bills or on the feathers of their heads.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Andrew B. Hingston |author2=Brett D. Gartell |author3=Gina Pinchbeck |last-author-amp=yes |year=2004 |title=How specialized is the plant\u2013pollinator association between ''Eucalyptus globulus'' ssp. ''globulus'' and the swift parrot ''Lathamus discolor''? |journal=[[Austral Ecology]] |volume=29 |issue=6 |pages=624\u2013630 |doi=10.1111/j.1442-9993.2004.01397.x}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|32em}}\n\n==External links and further reading==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.parks.tas.gov.au/wildlife/birds/yelwattle.html |title=Yellow Wattlebird, ''Anthochaera paradoxa'' |work=Wildlife of Tasmania |publisher=[[Department of Primary Industries, Parks, Water and Environment]] |date=5 March 2008 |accessdate=25 April 2008}}\n* {{cite book |editor=Sandy Podulka |editor2=Ronald W. Rohrbaugh |editor3=Nick Booney |year=2004 |title=Handbook of Bird Biology |edition=2nd |location=Ithaca, NY |publisher=Cornell Laboratory of Ornithology |isbn=093802762X}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q226136}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:wattlebird, yellow}}\n[[Category:Anthochaera|yellow wattlebird]]\n[[Category:Endemic birds of Tasmania]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1800|yellow wattlebird]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n", "text_old": "{{speciesbox\n| name = Yellow wattlebird\n| image = Anthochaera paradoxa.jpg\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=IUCN>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22704469/0 |title=''Anthochaera paradoxa'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| genus = Anthochaera\n| species = paradoxa\n| authority = ([[Francois-Marie Daudin|Daudin]], 1800)\n| synonyms = ''Corvus paradoxus'' <small>Daudin, 1800</small>\n}}\n\nThe '''yellow wattlebird''' (''Anthochaera paradoxa'') is a species of [[bird]] in the honeyeater family, [[Meliphagidae]].<ref name=IUCN/> Other names include the long or Tasmanian wattlebird.<ref name=\"Pizzey\">{{cite book |author=Graham Pizzey |author-link=Graham Pizzey |year=1980 |title=[[A Field Guide to the Birds of Australia (Pizzey)|A Field Guide to the Birds of Australia]] |location=Australia |publisher=[[Angus and Robertson]] |isbn=9780691084831}}</ref>\n\n==Taxonomy==\nFrench zoologist, [[Fran\u00e7ois Marie Daudin]], described the yellow wattlebird in 1800 as ''Corvus paradoxus''.\n\n==Description==\nThe yellow wattlebird is the largest of the honeyeaters,<ref name=\"Simpson\">{{cite journal |author1=Ken Simpson  |author2=Nicolas Day  |lastauthoramp=yes |year=2004 |title=[[Field Guide to the Birds of Australia (Simpson & Day)|Field Guide to the Birds of Australia]] |edition=7th |location=Princeton, NJ |publisher=[[Princeton University Press]] |isbn=9780691120492}}</ref> and is endemic to Tasmania. They are usually {{convert|37.5|-|45|cm|0}} long.<ref name=\"Pizzey\"/> They are named for the [[Wattle (anatomy)|wattles]] hanging from the cheeks.<ref name=MM>Morcombe, Michael (2012) Field guide to Australian birds. Pascal Press, Glebe, NSW. Revised edition. ISBN 978174021417-9</ref> Yellow wattlebirds are slim birds with a short, strong bill.<ref name=\"Backyard\"/> They have a white face and black-streaked crown.<ref name=\"Simpson\"/> They also have a long, pendulous yellow-orange wattle.<ref name=\"Simpson\"/> The wattle becomes brighter during the breeding season.<ref name=\"Backyard\"/> They have dark wings and a yellow belly,<ref name=\"Simpson\"/> whereas the upperparts are grey to dusky brown.<ref name=\"Pizzey\"/> The female yellow wattlebird is much smaller than the male.<ref name=\"Simpson\"/> The young yellow wattlebirds have much smaller wattles, a paler head, and a browner underbelly than the adult birds.<ref name=\"Backyard\"/> Yellow wattlebirds are active and acrobatic with a strong flight.<ref name=\"Pizzey\"/> They are fairly tame birds and often enter gardens looking for food.<ref name=\"Pizzey\"/>\n\nThe yellow wattlebird is similar in appearance to the [[little wattlebird]] and the [[red wattlebird]].\n\n==Voice==\nHarsh, raucous and grating, their calls have often been compared to a person [[coughing]] or [[belching]], <ref name=\"Pizzey\"/> with a gurgling ''growk'' or repeated ''clok'' sound<ref name=MM></ref>\n\n==Breeding==\nYellow wattlebirds nest in breeding pairs and aggressively defend their territories from other birds.<ref name=\"Backyard\"/> The nest of the yellow wattlebird is made by the female alone,<ref name=\"Backyard\"/> and is a large, open saucer-shaped structure made of twigs and bark that are bound by wool.<ref name=\"Pizzey\"/> The inside of the nest is lined with wool and grass.<ref name=\"Pizzey\"/> The nests can be up to {{convert|13|cm}} high and are found in trees or shrubs.<ref name=\"Pizzey\"/> Yellow wattlebirds lay 2\u20133 eggs that are salmon-red, spotted and blotched red-brown, purplish-red and blue-grey.<ref name=\"Pizzey\"/> Both the males and females incubate the egg and feed the young.<ref name=\"Backyard\"/>\n\n==Habitat==\nYellow wattlebirds live in a variety of habitats including both dry and wet forests, and from sea level to the [[subalpine zone]].<ref name=\"Backyard\"/> They live in coastal [[heath]]s, forests and gardens near ''[[Eucalyptus]]'' trees.<ref name=\"Simpson\"/> They also can be found in mountain shrubberies and open woodlands, particularly those dominated by ''[[Banksia]]''.<ref name=\"Pizzey\"/> They have also been known to occur on [[golf course]]s, and in [[orchard]]s, parks and gardens.<ref name=\"Pizzey\"/>\n\n==Range==\nYellow wattlebirds are common in Tasmania, especially in the eastern and central areas.<ref name=\"Backyard\">{{cite web |url=http://birdsinbackyards.net/finder/display.cfm?id=288 |title=Yellow Wattlebird |publisher=Birds in Backyards |date=11 April 2006 |accessdate=28 April 2008}}</ref> They are also found on [[King Island (Tasmania)|King Island]] and two sightings have been recorded on the southern [[Mornington Peninsula]] in [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]].<ref name=\"Pizzey\"/>\n\n==Ecology==\nYellow wattlebirds feed on the [[nectar]] of eucalypts and banksias, fruit, [[insect]]s, [[spider]]s, [[Honeydew (secretion)|honeydew]] and manna (crystallised plant sap).<ref name=\"Action\">{{cite web |url=http://www.environment.gov.au/biodiversity/threatened/publications/action/birds2000/pubs/yellow-wattlebird.pdf |format=[[Portable Document Format|PDF]] |title=The Action Plan for Australian Birds 2000: Recovery Outline \u2013 Yellow Wattlebird (King Island) |publisher=[[Department of the Environment, Water, Heritage and the Arts]] |date=27 April 2008 |accessdate=28 April 2008}}</ref> They forage from all levels of the canopy from the ground to the top of the trees.<ref name=\"Backyard\"/> However, the blossoming of eucalyptus trees can be highly irregular in time and place causing considerable changes from year to year in the breeding distribution of yellow wattlebirds, which rely on the nectar from the eucalyptus trees as a main source of food.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=M. G. Ridpath  |author2=R. E. Moreau  |lastauthoramp=yes |year=1966 |title=The birds of Tasmania: ecology and evolution |journal=[[Ibis (journal)|Ibis]] |volume=108 |issue=3 |pages=348\u2013393 |doi=10.1111/j.1474-919X.1966.tb07349.x}}</ref> Therefore, the most likely threat to the yellow wattlebird is unusual climatic conditions that can reduce food availability suddenly.<ref name=\"Action\"/> Yellow wattlebirds can pollinate eucalyptus trees by carrying pollen in their bills or on the feathers of their heads.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Andrew B. Hingston |author2=Brett D. Gartell |author3=Gina Pinchbeck |last-author-amp=yes |year=2004 |title=How specialized is the plant\u2013pollinator association between ''Eucalyptus globulus'' ssp. ''globulus'' and the swift parrot ''Lathamus discolor''? |journal=[[Austral Ecology]] |volume=29 |issue=6 |pages=624\u2013630 |doi=10.1111/j.1442-9993.2004.01397.x}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|32em}}\n\n==External links and further reading==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.parks.tas.gov.au/wildlife/birds/yelwattle.html |title=Yellow Wattlebird, ''Anthochaera paradoxa'' |work=Wildlife of Tasmania |publisher=[[Department of Primary Industries, Parks, Water and Environment]] |date=5 March 2008 |accessdate=25 April 2008}}\n* {{cite book |editor=Sandy Podulka |editor2=Ronald W. Rohrbaugh |editor3=Nick Booney |year=2004 |title=Handbook of Bird Biology |edition=2nd |location=Ithaca, NY |publisher=Cornell Laboratory of Ornithology |isbn=093802762X}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q226136}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:wattlebird, yellow}}\n[[Category:Anthochaera|yellow wattlebird]]\n[[Category:Endemic birds of Tasmania]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1800|yellow wattlebird]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n", "name_user": "Rogermccart", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRange:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yellow_wattlebird"}
